04089nam a22005895i 9780889207622DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19791979xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892076227 a10.51644/97808892076222doi  a(DE-B1597)667252  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJC73 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.52231 aHutter, Horst, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitics As Friendship :bThe Origins of Classical Notions of Politics in the Theory and Practice of Friendship /cHorst Hutter. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[1979] 4cÂ©1979  a1 online resource (214 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tFriendship and Enmity -- tThe Social and Political Context of Greek Theories of Friendship -- tThe Psychodynamics of Greek Friendship -- tAn Overview of Greek Theories of Friendship -- tAmicitia and Concordia: Friendship in the Life and Times of Cicero -- tFriendship in Modern Society -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHutter's study explores the origins of classical conceptions of politics in the theory and practice of friendship in ancient Greece. It analyzes ancient Greek society as one in which political space was organized in terms of the metaphor of friendship. Tracing the importance of male friendship groupings in Greek society, and comparing them to similar formations in primitive societies known to us through anthropological data, it shows how political processes were conceived as friendship processes, and demonstrates how important friendship groupings were for these processes. Greek political philosophies are seen as universalizations of the principles of friendship. Hutter shows to what extent Platonism and Aristotlelianism as well as Stoicism received their inspiration from the practice of friendship. In particular, the theory and practice of Greek democracy are seen to be derived from the principles of friendship. Finally, the book shows the application of Greek theories of friendship to Roman society by Cicero. Noting the differences and similarities between Greece and Rome, it explores the redefinition that the theory of friendship underwent when applied to the Roman context. The concluding chapter briefly discusses the role of friendship in mass society and its politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFriendshipxGreecexRome (Empire). 0aFriendship. 0aPolitical sciencexHistoryxGreece. 0aPolitical sciencexHistoryxRome. 0aPolitical sciencezGreecexHistory. 0aPolitical sciencezRomexHistory. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science: International Relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920762240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207622423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207622/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles